        <section type="subsection">
        <title>Power</title>
<para>If the current and voltage are functions of time, so they are always changing, then so will the power that is dissipated in any circuit element. In circuits which contain only ohmic resistors the <emphasis effect='bold'>average</emphasis> power dissipated in any component can be calculated in terms of the rms values. </para>
        <latex display='block'>
            \begin{align}
                P_{av} &amp;=I_{rms}V_{rms} \\
                        &amp;=\frac{I_{\max}}{\sqrt{<number>2</number>}}\frac{V_{\max}}{\sqrt{<number>2</number>}}\\
                        &amp;=\frac{<number>1</number>}{<number>2</number>}I_{\max}V_{\max}
            \end{align}
        </latex>
        <para>You might ask why we don't need to use an rms value for power. In an AC circuit both the current and voltage have the same sign so they are both either positive or negative. This means that power, the product of the two is always positive. If power is always positive then the average value won't be zero as in the case of current or voltage in AC circuits.</para>

        <worked_example>
        <title>Laptop transformer power</title>
        <question>
        <para>The transformer for a laptop has the following information: 
            <list>
                <item>INPUT: <number>100</number>-<unit_number><number>240</number><unit>V</unit></unit_number>; <unit_number><number>1.5</number><unit>A</unit></unit_number>; <number>50</number>/<unit_number><number>60</number><unit>Hz</unit></unit_number></item>
                <item>OUTPUT:<unit_number><number>20</number><unit>V</unit></unit_number>; <unit_number><number>3.25</number><unit>A</unit></unit_number></item>
            </list> 
            </para>
        <para>
        Using the input values and assuming <unit_number><number>240</number><unit>V</unit></unit_number>, what is the average power dissipated in the transformer?
        </para>
        </question>
        <answer>
        <workstep>
        <title>RMS values</title>
        <para>As calculated previously:</para>
        <latex display="block">
         \begin{align}
         V_{\textrm{rms}} &amp; =  \frac{V_{\textrm{max}}}{\sqrt{<number>2</number>}} \\
         V_{\textrm{rms}} &amp; =  \frac{<unit_number><number>240</number><unit>V</unit></unit_number>}{\sqrt{<number>2</number>}} \\
         &amp; = <unit_number><number>169.71</number><unit>V</unit></unit_number>
         \end{align}
         </latex><para>Therefore <latex>V_{\textrm{rms}}=<unit_number><number>169.71</number><unit>V</unit></unit_number></latex></para>

        <latex display="block">
         \begin{align}
         I_{\textrm{rms}} &amp; =  \frac{I_{\textrm{max}}}{\sqrt{<number>2</number>}} \\
         I_{\textrm{rms}} &amp; =  \frac{<unit_number><number>1.5</number><unit>A</unit></unit_number>}{\sqrt{<number>2</number>}} \\
         &amp; = <unit_number><number>1.06</number><unit>A</unit></unit_number>
         \end{align}
         </latex><para>Therefore <latex>I_{\textrm{rms}}=<unit_number><number>1.06</number><unit>A</unit></unit_number></latex></para>
        </workstep>
        <workstep>
            <title>Average power</title>
        <latex display='block'>
            \begin{align}
                P_{av} &amp;=I_{rms}V_{rms} \\
                        &amp;= <unit_number><number>1.06</number><unit>A</unit></unit_number> \cdot  <unit_number><number>169.71</number><unit>V</unit></unit_number>\\
                        &amp; = <unit_number><number>179.89</number><unit>W</unit></unit_number>
            \end{align}
        </latex>
        </workstep>
        </answer>
        </worked_example>
